  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Renewing irrigation assets</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Poor farmers in northern Malawi live on what they can grow. They barter or sell any surplus food in local markets to buy clothes and essentials, leaving no cash for healthcare or secondary education. Many farmers only have a small amount of land available which they have used to grow suitable and small-scale cash crops like paprika with a guaranteed market. Irrigated land can double the yields of these crops and protect staple foods. However, many past schemes to introduce irrigation have failed due to technical flaws, inappropriate design and lack of training. This project identifies failed schemes which, where possible can be fixed up and made more sustainable. It helps farmers to satisfy their needs, and builds a business case to attract investors so more farmers can benefit.</narrative>
  </description>
